Regarding this report from a month ago (and the related bug):

We haven&#39;t noticed this, but I can think of an atypical situation
where this might happen in a single crawl:

  - if mid-crawl, you changed the URI canoncalization rules in
    effect, then a subsequent discovery of the same URI wouldn&#39;t
    necessarily be canonicalized the same way as the first, and
    thus not recognized as &quot;already included&quot;

Also, if you use the &#39;recover&#39; crawl capability to simulate the
resumption of a previous crawl, the current behavior is to recrawl
the seeds -- they&#39;re scheduled in the new crawl *before* the
previous crawl&#39;s recovery log is processed. (This is somewhat a
bug, but we&#39;ve sometimes found it useful, so we haven&#39;t made
fixing it a priority.)

However, in this case I see that the two fetches are immediately
after each other, and in the same ARC file -- so no settings changes
or recoveries could have happened.

Also helpful to determine what&#39;s happened would be to grep through
the associated crawl.log for the affected URI -- to see what it says
about the two fetches. (Were they both recognized as successful?
Both &#39;via&#39; the same predecessor URI? etc.)

Depending on what that indicates, looking for the URI or any other
errors in the heritrix-out.log or local-errors.log around the time
of the dual-fetch might shed light on the situation.

- Gordon @ IA

